<HEADLINE>
FT  20 AUG 92 / International Company News: Warning by American Airlines
hits sector shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US AIRLINE shares tumbled yesterday after American Airlines, one of the
industry's three 'mega-carriers', warned that it expects to make a sizeable
loss in the third quarter.
American, one of the most tightly-run US carriers, is widely viewed as a
bell-wether for the industry. Like most of its rivals, it has already
reported losses for the second quarter, and for the first six months of
1992.
American's warning came in a conference call between Mr Michael Durham, the
company's finance director, and analysts. 'The industry environment
continues to be extremely difficult,' said Mr Durham. He added that,
although American's effort to rationalise fare structures had boosted
traffic, yields were 'severely depressed'.
'As a result, we expect our third-quarter loss to exceed that of the second
quarter, adjusted for the loss provision relating to the Confirm Reservation
development project,' he said.
In the second quarter, AMR - American's parent company - reported a loss of
Dollars 166m after tax. Part of this deficit came from one-off items -
including a Dollars 109m provision on Confirm, the now-suspended hotel and
car reservation system project. But without these charges, AMR said it would
still have posted a Dollars 48m after-tax loss. Mr Durham's comments suggest
that the third quarter deficit will exceed this Dollars 48m figure.
</TEXT>
