<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 92 / Despatch of jets gesture to US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S decision last night to contribute six Tornado aircraft to the
multinational forces ranged against President Saddam Hussein in the Gulf is
a political gesture appreciated in Washington but one which makes little
difference to the balance of forces in the region.
The Royal Air Force performed bravely during the Gulf war and suffered
relatively heavy losses as the Tornados initially pressed home low-level
attacks on well-defended Iraqi targets. The six aircraft being sent this
week will probably be again based in Bahrain, although on this occasion
their primary role appears more likely to be surveillance and interdiction.
The US military presence in the Gulf is massive and it will be on American
forces and equipment that the overwhelming burden of the operation will
fall.
According to latest Pentagon statistics the US has 19 ships in the Gulf,
headed by the aircraft carrier Independence, the command vessel LaSalle,
three cruisers, one destroyer, two frigates, six support ships and five
amphibious craft.
No precise figures are provided for aircraft but those based in Saudi Arabia
and on the Independence are known to exceed 200. They provide a range of
options for military commanders and include the F-117 Stealth fighters,
which are supposed to be almost invisible to radar, the F-14 and F-15e,
Awacs surveillance aircraft and the A-10 'tank-busters' that inflicted such
heavy damage on Iraqi armoured concentrations during the final days of the
Gulf war.
In addition the US has ground forces exercising in Kuwait with the 2,800
marines already there due to be augmented soon by 2,400 regular troops. The
Pentagon said yesterday that its military personnel in the Gulf totalled
23,800. Mr Pete Williams, the Pentagon spokesman, added he did not believe
there were any immediate plans to augment those forces.
Once the exclusion zone is officially announced  - probably via a letter
from the US, Britain and France to Iraq's ambassador at the UN - any of
Saddam Hussein's fixed-wing aircraft or helicopters flying south of the 32nd
parallel can expect to be attacked.
Iraq's pilots have not in the past been anxious to risk their aircraft in
combat and there is even less reason this time to believe that they will
challenge the allies. During the eight-year war with Iran, Mr Saddam made
relatively little use of his overwhelming air superiority, reserving it
mainly to attack shipping in the Gulf and fly the occasional high-level
mission over Tehran.
Soon after the outbreak of the Gulf war last year the Iraqi leader ordered
dozens of his front-line aircraft to flee to Iran, where many of them
remain. However, in recent weeks it has been evident to the US that Iraqi
training flights have been increasing, although probably fewer than 100
aircraft are serviceable. While they would be no match for US and British
aircraft, it is their potential role in attacking Shia rebels that the
exclusion zone is meant to prevent.
There have been recent, if limited, cases of helicopter gunships and the
occasional fixed-wing aircraft attacking rebel positions in the marshes area
north of Basra. US officials believe that without a firm western response,
the number of sorties flown by Mr Saddam's air force would have steadily
increased.
However military analysts acknowledge that there is a limited scope for
aircraft to protect the Shia insurgents, without extending the exclusion
zone to include movements of armour and troops. President George Bush
remains anxious to avoid being sucked in further to the Iraqi quagmire, but
the collapse of the Iraqi regime remains the US objective.
Mr Paul Ride, 33, a Briton who disappeared in the Kuwaiti desert in
unexplained circumstances seven weeks ago, was understood to be 'well' in a
Baghdad jail, the Foreign Office said yesterday, writes David Owen in
London. He vanished in June while travelling between two of his employer's
offices in northern Kuwait.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
