<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 92 / Bosnian winter will place 2m at risk
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY and AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE bitterly cold winters which sweep across the Balkan peninsula will claim
the lives of many more people in Bosnia-Hercegovina unless conditions
rapidly improve in the former Yugoslav republic, officials from the United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees said yesterday.
The people most affected will be the thousands held in detentions camps, but
as many as 2m people in the Bosnian war zone could be at risk.
'Not only is there massive destruction of buildings but there are no windows
left,' said Mr Charles Lamuniere, director of the UN department of
Humanitarian Affairs.
'So when those winds start blowing  - you know, Sarajevo is in a valley and
the wind will start blowing  - people will die of cold, water will freeze.'
Mr Lamuniere said he was particularly concerned about those prisoners in
detention camps. He specifically referred to 3,000 Moslem men he saw in the
Serbian-run camp at Manjaca, northern Bosnia. He said the detainees were
forced to sleep on cold concrete floors.
Ms Sylvana Foa, of UNHCR said that about 200 homes were being destroyed
every day. 'We're really worried about everyone in the war zone. That's
about 2m pople. Time is very pressing. We probably have another eight weeks
before it gets cold.'
The UNHCR needed personnel, supplies, heating equipment, blankets and
plastic sheeting to cover up the windows, she said.
Getting massive aid supplies into Bosnia will require guarantees of safe
passage, particularly by the Bosnia Serbs and Serb irregulars, a western
diplomat said.
Meanwhile, there was a hopeful sign in the Bosnian conflict last night when
leaders of the warring factions agreed to UN supervision of all heavy
weapons around Sarajevo.
'If this agreement works, there will be no shelling in Sarajevo,' Mr Zaim
Backovic, a deputy commander of the Bosnian forces, said.
The agreement, concentrating heavy weapons in areas under UN supervision,
would enable monitors to determine who is responsible for shelling and to
pressure violators to stop. It was signed by Serb nationalist and Bosnian
government leaders.
However, western caution about the conflict could be enhanced by a threat
yesterday to an RAF relief flight at Sarajevo airport. UNHCR suspended
humanitarian relief flights after the incident, but the airport remained
open.
No military intervention was planned against the forces who apparently
'locked on' to a RAF Hercules transport with radar equipment designed to
target objects for attack, the UN said in New York. It said other flights
would continue, including one due to bring Gen Satish Nambiar, head of UN
peacekeepers in Yugoslavia.
A senior UN source in Sarajevo said earlier that UN headquarters was
evaluating the incident and that it could lead to an air strike against the
gun position.
The incident, less than a week after a UN Security Council resolution
allowing the use of force to get supplies to trapped civilians, seemed sure
to heighten tension and increase the probability of foreign military action
in the area. A strike would have been the first direct foreign military
intervention against one of the warring parties in the four-month-old Bosnia
conflict.
In addition to the problems posed by the pending winter, western diplomats
say that Mr Radovan Karadzic, head of Bosnia's Serbs, continues to sanction
the process of 'ethnic cleansing', by which whole communities are forced to
leave their homes.
In addition the diplomats say he is not prepared to lift the siege of
Sarajevo, the eastern Bosnian town of Gorazde, and the northern city of
Bihac.
'We must not forget that Sarajevo, a European city, is still being
bombarded. People, most Moslems, are being forced to sign away their
property, then they are forced to flee. UN or European Community resolutions
have not stopped the killing,' an EC diplomat said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
