<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 92 / UK takes cautious troops decision: London wants to be seen
doing something to help a settlement in Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY, Eastern Europe correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DECISION by Britain to send up to 1,800 troops to Bosnia-Hercegovina is
a cautious and limited exercise aimed at boosting the UN's already
overstretched capacity to protect international humanitarian relief
operations.
It is also designed to reassure public opinion that Britain, as current
president of the European Community, is prepared to be seen to be doing
something which, in the long term, could form the basis for some negotiated
settlement in Bosnia.
But western diplomats and defence experts last night conceded that the
British gestures would do little in the way of stopping the fighting and
killing in the former Yugoslav republic.
'If London wanted to help in the humanitarian effort, maybe this will help,'
an EC diplomat said. 'But I am doubtful  - and we are all in the same
position  - if this will stop the fighting.'
Mr John Major, the prime minister, had four options:
Provide light military support and escorts for the aid convoys, and with the
consent of the three sides which are fighting in Bosnia;
Provide relief convoys, and go through to besieged towns, but without the
consent of any side. Those convoys would also defend themselves in the
process;
Provide relief supported by heavily armed relief convoys which would fight
their way to their targets;
Set up permanent security corridors in parts of Bosnia-Hercegovina.
The last three options were ruled out partly because it would require at
least 100,000 ground troops and, besides, the UN operations in Bosnia would
have to be withdrawn because their impartiality would be completely
undermined.
Moreover, British officials last night stressed that option one would only
be implemented 'on the understanding that all three sides in the conflict in
Bosnia consented to these forces, which would be operating under the
auspices of the UN blue helmets,' an official said.
Officials from the United Nations High Commissioner on Refugees had earlier
in the week asked western governments not to endorse any international
military intervention because it would also undermine the UNHCR's own
operations throughout the republic.
'We had to take into consideration all these aspects. We have stuck to the
humanitarian effort because we are afraid of ending up in a Vietnam or
Beirut situation,' a British defence attache said last night.
Indeed, the British government last night insisted that the 'maximum' of
1,800 would be sent to Bosnia, thus confirming Mr Major's reluctance to
become embroiled in the war.
The British response to the bloodshed in Bosnia was greeted with mixed
response by defence specialists and EC diplomats.
Mr James Gow, a specialist on the Yugoslav army at Centre for Defence
Studies at London's Kings College, said the British initiative did not
really add up to anything substantial.
'The decision by the government gives the impression that it is prepared to
do something. But if you look at it in detail, it does very little. It is
predicated on too many ifs,' he said. British troops will only be sent if
requested by the UNHCR, and they will escort aid convoys which are operating
with the consent of all sides in Bosnia.
Essentially, Britain has decided to act within the strict confines of last
week's UN Security Council meeting which stated that 'all measures
necessary' would be used to protect the aid convoys. Force, or the use of
force, was not mentioned in the resolution.
Moreover, western diplomats last night said that by acting under the UN flag
 - which meant that British troops would wear blue helmets, the UN colours
 -they were bound to remain impartial in the war in Bosnia-Hercegovina.
British diplomats said London's decision corresponded to those of other
European capitals. But the question now facing western governments is how
this decision will be interpreted by Bosnia's Serbs, who continue to besiege
Sarajevo, the Bosnian capital, Gorazde, in eastern Bosnia, and Bihac, in the
north of the republic.
'Is this another green light for the aggressor to grab more land and expel
more people?' a US diplomat asked. 'Will this mean that Bosnia's Moslems
have nothing left to lose so they will fight to the bitter end to defend
themselves?'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
