<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 92 / Major orders fighters to Gulf: Britain pledges 1,800 troops
to escort UN relief convoys in Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and ROGER MATTHEWS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN last night responded to the conflicts in southern Iraq and
Bosnia-Hercegovina by deciding to send warplanes to the Gulf and offering up
to 1,800 troops to escort United Nations aid convoys in the former Yugoslav
republic.
After a six-hour meeting with senior ministers, Mr John Major, the prime
minister, announced that six Tornado jet fighters and two refuelling
aircraft would join an international force to clamp a 'no-fly' zone on
southern Iraq. This will stop Iraq from using its aircraft to attack Shia
Moslems in the area.
Officials said any troops sent to Bosnia would be under the UN flag to
escort convoys operating with the consent of the warring factions. It was
stressed at the highest levels in Downing Street that there was no question
of the troops being used to 'fight a way through to besieged towns' in the
republic, which is torn by ethnic conflict between Serbs, Croats and
Moslems. Troops would not be sent to 'fight their way to Armageddon and
back', one senior minister said.
France yesterday also announced support for the US plan to curb President
Saddam Hussein by enforcing an air exclusion zone in southern Iraq.
Mr Major said the exclusion zone, to be set up within days, was a response
to 'clear evidence' that Mr Saddam had adopted a policy of 'systematic
murder, genocide' of the area's Shia Moslems.
The international coalition of forces ranged against Iraq would fly 24-hour
air patrols over southern Iraq, mainly with US aircraft, but France had
agreed to contribute a force similar in size to that of the UK, he said.
Mr Major expected the Iraqi air force would stop bombing the Shia
communities, but added: 'If they fly in the proscribed area, then they will
be attacked.'
Rejecting suggestions that the operation was being mounted to help the
re-election prospects of President George Bush in November, Mr Major charged
Mr Saddam with repeatedly flouting UN resolutions by 'systematic repression'
of the Shias.
Officials said the Tornados  - which can be used in both combat and
reconnaissance roles  - would be in the region within days. There was
speculation they would be based in Bahrain, from which they operated during
the Gulf war.
The international force would operate under existing UN resolutions but the
precise scope of the zone would be finalised in discussions at the Security
Council in New York, officials said. A note warning Iraq would then be
handed to the Iraqi ambassador at the UN.
Mr Major, who broke off his holiday in Spain to chair yesterday's emergency
ministerial talks, signalled that the plan to send a maximum of 1,800
British forces personnel to Bosnia did not represent a reversal of his
strong opposition to direct western military involvement in the Yugoslav
conflict.
The personnel would form part of an enlarged UN force in the region, and
would be sent only if requested by UN aid agencies.
The offer of troops comes after the Security Council authorised the use of
force if necessary to get humanitarian aid to civilians in Bosnia. France
has already sent troops to Bosnia to help the relief effort.
A range of more ambitious options was considered and rejected at the London
meeting, including a defensive role against light attacks on convoys
operating without the agreement of the protagonists, a defensive role
against heavier attacks and opening up permanently defended aid corridors.
But officials said each had been rejected because of the risk of drawing
western forces into a full-scale conflict.
A British Hercules transport aircraft found itself under threat yesterday as
it was taking off from Sarajevo, the Bosnian capital, after delivering
relief supplies. A UN official said irregular forces in the hills locked on
to the aircraft with radar equipment designed to target objects for attack.
The US, meanwhile, is not planning to seek a fresh UN Security Council
mandate before enforcing a ban on Iraqi aircraft flying south of the 32nd
parallel. It believes resolutions passed at the end of the Gulf war are
worded broadly enough to allow military action in defence of the groups
being persecuted by Baghdad.
Shia rebels in southern Iraq have come under intensified military pressure
from Baghdad in recent weeks. US officials say they have detected a large
buildup of Iraqi troops in the south.
Mr Roland Dumas, French foreign minister, said that the exclusion zone
imposed in northern Iraq to protect the Kurdish population had proved
effective. 'So we envisage, among the allies, going about things the same
way over southern Iraq to protect the Shia population,' he said.
