<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 92 / International Company News: Mannesmann bravado is now thin
on the ground
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOME of the pioneering bravado has waned in the 2 1/2 years since Mannesmann
won its licence to operate Germany's first cellular telephone system  - a
move which marked its first significant departure from its traditional
engineering business, writes Christopher Parkes.
The initial total investment of Dollars 800m has drained group resources at
a time when profits have been squeezed by international recession and a
slow-down in home markets.
However, the network is up and running. Mannesmann, which owns 51 per cent
of Mobilfunk, along with partners Pacific Telesis of the US (26 per cent),
DG Bank (10 per cent), Cable &amp; Wireless (5 per cent), Lyonnaise des Eaux
(2.5 per cent) expect great things. But not quite yet.
Consumer confidence in Germany is low and falling. National retail sales
fell 6 per cent in July, just as D2 Privat, as it is known, and D1, the
federal telecommunications utility's competitor, made their debut.
So far it has about 10,000 subscribers, and has given itself nine years to
hit 2m. It aims to break even in 1994. But while the partners have been
spending, the Bonn telecommunications ministry has grown increasingly
enchanted by the notion of competition and mobile phones for all. Mr
Christian Schwarz-Schilling, the minister responsible, called in June for
bids for a licence for an E1 network.
It is potentially more flexible and cheaper than D1 and D2 and it is likely
to present a formidable challenge that was unforeseen when Mannesmann took
the plunge.
</TEXT>
