<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 92 / Sponsors steer clear of Soviet coup festivities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ATTEMPTS to win private-sector backing for celebrations in Moscow to mark
the defeat of the Soviet coup a year ago have ended in chaos.
The organising committee, taking into account the dire state of Russia's
finances, sought sponsorship for the festivities from the many private
businesses established since the Soviet grip on the economy was loosened.
The committee asked a private company to take on the task of finding
sponsorship for the estimated Rbs70m-90m cost of the 'Vivat Rossiya' (Long
live Russia) celebrations.
But the company failed to deliver, blaming the lack of a role for a
principal sponsor and the absence of an interest-free loan from the state.
Mr Grigory Andreyev, a member of the organising committee, said an afternoon
of band music and entertainment scheduled for Red Square on Saturday was one
of the casualties.
He said the celebrations were important because 'we still hope that what
started in August will prevail . . . that democracy and freedom will
prevail'.
While the state as usual is expected to stump up some money at the last
minute, recriminations are rife over who is responsible for the debacle.
The director of one Moscow advertising agency, who said he stood on the
barricades last year, had advised his clients against providing finance
because there was no principal sponsor slot.
Still to go ahead are a voluntary gathering tonight of people who 'defended'
President Boris Yeltsin's 'White House' against Soviet army tanks, as well
as a rally attended by Russian leaders tomorrow. There will also be a
service tomorrow in memory of the three young people who died when tanks
rumbled through Moscow, followed by brass-band and rock concerts on
Saturday.
More traditional methods have been used in St Petersburg, Russia's second
largest city. The celebrations are to be financed by a Rbs800,000 grant from
the city budget, although the prospect of 'freedom marches' organised by the
city authorities is reminiscent of old-style birthday celebrations for the
Communist Youth League.
Some inhabitants were also bemused by plans to award 600 medals to defenders
of freedom in the city when tanks came nowhere near it. Mayor Anatoly
Sobchak will have returned from a holiday in Barcelona in time to preside
over the proceedings, although his city's economic situation is as dire as
Moscow's.
However, the razzmatazz may fall rather flat. Public indifference has long
replaced the euphoria which followed the coup's collapse on August 21,
suggesting that there is little demand for celebrations.
A year after the coup, Page 3
</TEXT>
