<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 92 / Management: Take the high road - James Buxton and Lisa Wood
assess whether Tecs should have a Scottish-style central body
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON and LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
While English and Welsh Training and Enterprise Councils ponder whether to
press the government to create a new central body to co-ordinate and support
them, they are directing their eyes northwards to Scotland.
In Scotland the equivalent of Tecs, the Local Enterprise Companies (Lecs),
were born at the same time as their umbrella organisations. Outside the
Highlands the Lecs come under Scottish Enterprise, while in the Highlands
their parent body is Highlands and Islands Enterprise. These bodies have
their own strategic development function and also act as a useful buffer
between the Lecs and central government.
It may be partly because of this difference with England  - where Tecs
contract directly with the government  - that the Lecs appear more
successful than the Tecs and on the whole have looked happier than their
southern counterparts.
In Scotland the creation of Lecs was part of a drastic reorganisation of two
long-established bodies, the Scottish Development Agency and the Highlands
and Islands Development Board. Their successors, Scottish Enterprise and
Highlands and Islands Enterprise, devolved many economic development powers
to the new enterprise companies, which also took over training functions
from the Training Agency.
So although both Tecs and Lecs have responsibility for training and business
development, the 13 Lecs under Scottish Enterprise in lowland Scotland have
a much stronger development function than do the Tecs and they resemble
mini-development agencies.
The Scottish Lecs have larger budgets in relation to their populations than
the Tecs. While nearly half their funds go on training, they also have
substantial budgets for environmental improvement work (including property
development) and business development.
Whereas in England some of the Tecs have had difficulty making themselves
known both to the business community and the public, in Scotland the public
sector has a higher profile, and the SDA and HIDB were already well known.
The creation of Scottish Enterprise's network of Lecs has released a great
deal of human energy into economic development. In Edinburgh, for example,
responsibility for development was devolved by Scottish Enterprise to
Lothian &amp; Edinburgh Enterprise Ltd (known as LEEL), a free-standing body
with a budget of Pounds 45m. LEEL has made an impact by backing projects
which required pulling together other bodies such as Edinburgh district
council and Lothian regional council.
Under its chairman Sir Charles Fraser, an energetic Edinburgh solicitor with
legendary contacts, it has brought Edinburgh's long nurtured dream of
creating an opera house closer to reality.
In Lanarkshire, south-east of Glasgow, the Lanarkshire Development Agency
has been given the task of regenerating the local economy after the closure
of British Steel's Ravenscraig plant. In Ayrshire, to the south-west of
Glasgow, Enterprise Ayrshire is drawing attention to an area of Scotland
which the SDA tended to neglect.
Some critics argue training is becoming a poor relation of high profile
environmental/property projects. The criticism does not apply to all Lecs:
several have made an attempt to integrate training with enterprise
development. At Enterprise Ayrshire training and business development are
interwoven in the management structure.
Under John Lord, its chief executive, Enterprise Ayrshire is trying to
escape the straitjacket of the official training programmes YT and ET, whose
names have been abandoned in favour of Ayrshire Skills Training. The aim is
to use knowledge of local companies to tailor training to their specific
needs.
Other critics fear that a development effort in lowland Scotland which was
formerly closely co-ordinated is being diffused or 'balkanised' as Lecs
pursue their own strategies, some of which may conflict with other Lecs.
Several of the Lecs, on the other hand, complain that they are excessively
constrained by Scottish Enterprise National (as the parent body, is now
known).
At Scottish Enterprise National, Crawford Beveridge, the chief executive,
says that the loose network is 'fulfilling the aim of applying local
solutions to local problems. Solutions are being found that would have been
unthinkable under the old monolithic structure.'
In reply to critics who argue that the network is too loose and that Lecs
are inclined to spend on the easy options such as environmental
improvements, he says that Lecs' budget requests are scrutinised to make
sure that they are in line with Scottish Enterprise's overall plan
Strategies for the 1990s.
In the 1992/93 bidding round for Scottish Enterprise's Pounds 400m budget
for the Lecs, the local enterprise companies overbid on property schemes and
underbid on projects to develop tourism and to 'internationalise' Scottish
business.
Mr Beveridge says the Scottish Enterprise network has 'a much more pragmatic
relationship with the Scottish Office than the Tecs have with the Training,
Enterprise and Education Division (TEED) of the Department of Employment'.
Many of the Tecs' dealings with TEED are very legalistic and they are
related to their contracts, he says, whereas the Lec chairmen only refer to
their contracts 'as a last resort'.
He also says that Scottish Enterprise's ability to get the 13 Lec chief
executives 'in a room together once every three months is a very powerful
management tool'.
As for the counter-criticism that Scottish Enterprise National, which itself
has a budget of Pounds 65m and employs 390 people, exercises too much
control over the Lecs, Beveridge replies: 'The Lecs are ambivalent about
this. When we ask them 'What should we be doing?' we get a longer list than
the list of what we actually do at the moment.
'We look at our support services and ask whether they should be here in
Glasgow or out at the Lecs. Three months ago I offered to split up our legal
department but the Lecs refused  - it would have put their costs up. But
I've promised I will go through all the support services function by
function to make sure that the services are being provided in the right
place.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 11
</PAGE>
