<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 92 / Warning on performance of pooled pension funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TOP performance by managers of pooled pension funds cannot be maintained
over a long period, according to a survey which raises questions about the
basis upon which such managers are selected.
Trustees of pension schemes and consultants frequently use past performance
as a guide to future returns. But Hymans Robertson, the firm of consulting
actuaries, attempted to find fund managers who had produced top-quartile
returns for each of three three-year periods between the years 1983 and
1991.
'No managers met this criteria,' it says in its 1992 pooled pension fund
survey.
Several managers were able to produce consistently above-average returns for
the whole period, but none could maintain a ranking in the top 25 per cent
of performers for any length of time.
Henderson Administration and Newton Investment Management were in the top
quartile in two of the three-year periods and had the most consistently good
investment performance.
Two managers, Crown Life and Provident Mutual, after achieving top returns
between 1983 and 1988, fell into the bottom quartile in the 1989-91 period,
while two others, Britannia Life and London and Manchester, ranked in the
top quartile between 1986 and 1991 but neither fund was available in the
1983-85 period.
The survey also found that segregated pension funds  - fund managed as
discreet entities  - tend to out-perform pooled funds run by the same
manager, in spite of the conventional wisdom that economies of scale allow
pooled funds to outperform.
In attempting to explain the divergence, Hymans Robertson said that fees
automatically deducted from clients in pooled funds may affect returns and
that the property exposure of pooled funds may also have undermined
performance.
</TEXT>
