FT  19 AUG 92 / Management (Training on Trial): Divisions over uniting
councils
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Training and Enterprise Councils will consider a broad range of options over
the next few weeks on how to co-ordinate their operations on a national
basis.
A shortlist of options prepared by Sir Christopher Ball, an academic, has
been presented to G10, the group of Tec chairmen who liase with the
government, and they will put proposals to Tecs this week.
The issue needs to be urgently resolved but because of the diversity of
opinion it is likely to provoke divisions between the 82 Tecs in England and
Wales. Indeed, discussion over a new intermediary body turned into a stormy
debate at the recent national Tec conference. Advocates of a strong
intermediary body, on the lines of Scottish Enterprise, claim it would give
them more clout with government and greater operating freedom.
The issue has risen to the top of Tecs' agendas because:
The National Training Task Force, a committee made up of leading businessmen
such as Sir Bryan Woolfson, chairman of Wembley Stadium, comes to the end of
its remit this year. While its main role has been to advise government on
setting up Tecs, it has taken on a number of other central responsibilities
such as getting the Investors in People Initiative (IIP) off the ground.
There is concern about G10, which is being asked to take on a greater
workload and is becoming over-stretched. Agendas for meetings at national
level have often contained too many topics with too little time for each.
The new national training targets, drawn up by the Confederation of British
Industry (CBI) and endorsed by many other organisations including the
government, need to be monitored nationally and examples of best practice
publicised.
The performance of Tecs vary, and because they have been fiercely
independent, there is a need for them to share best practice.
