<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 92 / Bank of England Quarterly Bulletin: Slow growth predicted
for late this year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SLOW economic growth should return to the UK later this year although the
outlook remains uncertain, according to a gloomy assessment published
yesterday by the Bank of England.
In its latest quarterly bulletin the Bank suggests that the recovery is
likely to be held back by the unwillingness of debt-laden consumers to
increase spending, the fragile world economy and thin order books in
industry.
One hopeful sign is falling inflation and low wage settlements. These
factors have aided manufacturing productivity and competitiveness, and were
partly reflected in the small growth in manufacturing output in the first
half of the year.
But the Bank sounds a warning over the widening trade deficit, caused by
increased import volumes. These have been 'surprisingly resilient given the
weakness of domestic demand throughout the recession'.
The assessment by the Bank, which was subject to vetting by the Treasury,
draws a distinction between increased spending by companies and continued
low consumer demand.
Companies spent more on buildings, plant and machinery in the first quarter,
apparently buoyed by hopes of stronger output later this year. This was the
first quarterly rise in investment since early 1990. Companies also stopped
reducing stocks of components and finished goods. Much of this activity
benefited overseas suppliers, showing up in the rise in imports.
But in the same three months consumer spending  - which accounts for two
thirds of gross domestic product  - fell 0.7 per cent compared with the
previous quarter. That was in spite of a 1 per cent rise in real disposable
incomes.
People's reluctance to increase spending is the main reason for the length
and seriousness of this recession. Consumer spending has fallen3.5 per cent
since mid-1990, compared with declines of less than 2 per cent in the
recessions of 1974-75 and 1980-81.
The Bank says 'significant numbers of people are saving more as they attempt
to repay some of the large amounts of debt accumulated in the late 1980s'
rather than increasing purchases of goods and services.
Interest payments on this debt  - a large proportion of which has comprised
mortgages  - have declined due to the 5 percentage-point fall in base rates
over the past two years to 10 per cent.
Even so, the Bank says, 'so far the personal sector has had only limited
success in cutting the scale of its debt in relation to income'.
The ratio of gross consumer debt to income fell by only 0.75 of a percentage
point from its peak of 91 per cent early last year.
Total personal sector borrowing as a proportion of assets  - the gearing
ratio  - increased to nearly 15 per cent at the end of last year (see
chart). Meanwhile, mortgage debt as a proportion of housing assets rose to
29 per cent. This figure has been pushed up by the decline in house prices
over the past four years.
According to the Bank, the fall in prices  - by about a quarter for some
parts of Britain  - has led to up to 1m mortgage holders having a mortgage
greater than the value of their home.
The Bank says falling inflation 'may have altered individuals' expectations
about the rate at which wage increases will enable households to outgrow
their existing debt'.
It adds: 'Highly geared households, which suffered a proportionately greater
squeeze on their incomes from high interest rates, are now suffering a
proportionately greater decline in their wealth as house prices fall.'
The UK outlook has been worsened by the depressed state of the world economy
'which continues to cause concern'. Across western Europe  - where borrowing
costs have been kept high due to high German interest rates  - the outlook
for the rest of this year 'is still fairly bleak'.
With the Japanese and US economies remaining subdued, growth this year among
the Group of Seven industrial nations  - the US, Japan, Germany, Italy,
France, Canada and Britain  - is expected to be less than 2 per cent.
Weakness in overseas markets has depressed export volumes, which are growing
less strongly than a year ago. Between the second half of last year and the
first half of this year non-oil export volumes rose 0.8 per cent. The
equivalent growth in imports was 4.9 per cent.
These changes have increased Britain's trade deficit on visible goods for
each of the past four quarters.
The Bank says the degree of import penetration partly reflects 'a sizeable
turnround in imports of consumer goods following a sharp reduction in such
imports earlier in the recession'.
The Bank draws a contrast with the sharp fall in imports during the previous
recession, when volumes fell 13 per cent between the beginning and the end
of 1980.
While the stronger activity by UK businesses this year  - some of which may
reflect their success in paying off debts and restoring their balance sheets
 - gives some grounds for optimism, the outlook for industry is patchy.
Business confidence was highly volatile in the first six months of this
year, leading to 'cautious hand-to-mouth ordering (which) has intensified
the uncertainties facing many companies'.
The Bank adds: 'Companies will continue to invest only if there is a
prospect of sustained growth of consumption and export demand'.
On the rapid recent increase in the public sector borrowing requirement, the
Bank says 'the uncertainty about the degree of slack in the economy makes it
difficult to judge the underlying fiscal position'. Meeting the Maastricht
standards on public sector debt will, however, require strict control of
public spending over the next few years.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
