FT  19 AUG 92 / Council's video system cuts crime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A VIDEO surveillance system set up by King's Lynn Borough Council in Norfolk
has cut car crime in the town centre and may be extended to include local
businesses.
The system was installed in February after the success of a pilot scheme on
a council-owned industrial estate where crime had been discouraging
businesses from moving in.
There are 36 cameras in car parks, housing estates and leisure and shopping
centres, linked by fibre-optic cables to a control room which is staffed 24
hours a day and has a direct link to the police.
Running the system costs Pounds 200,000 a year in staff, maintenance and
leasing costs. This is partly funded by a 5p surcharge on car-park tickets
and service charges for businesses covered by the scheme.
The system has cut vandalism and reduced car thefts from three a fortnight
to three in the six months since it was introduced. Police attribute 53
arrests directly to the cameras.
