<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 92 / Support for small businesses urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government is urging the banks to think hard about the longer-term
viability of small-business customers before deciding to withdraw support
from them.
With the government under mounting pressure to stimulate the economy,
Baroness Denton, small-business minister, is holding meetings with the
leading clearing banks to discuss the problems facing small businesses.
In an effort to stem mounting bankruptcies she is asking banks to 'spend
more time working out whether there is a future' before pulling the plug on
small-business customers. Insolvencies totalled 40,000 in the first half of
this year compared with 30,000 in the first six months of last year.
She has also extracted a commitment from all leading clearers to investigate
specific cases referred to them by her office. In keeping with a suggestion
made last year by Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, she is working towards a
voluntary code of best practice for banks in their dealings with
small-business customers.
Such a code might include recommendations such as a minimum warning period
to businesses before support is withdrawn, although the minister said she
was 'still listening at the moment'.
She said: 'I don't think the banks are unaware of their responsibilities.'
She emphasised that the banks would inevitably be the principal source of
funding for small businesses.
The initiative comes 10 months after the banks were criticised by the Office
of Fair Trading for their 'insensitive, high-handed' treatment of
small-business customers. Nevertheless it was decided to take no action
against them on competition grounds.
The watchdog's investigation followed a Treasury and Bank of England report,
commissioned by the government, which cleared the banks of colluding on
interest rates so as not to pass on to customers the benefit of lower
interest charges.
The banks yesterday insisted that withdrawal of their support was always a
last resort. Lloyds said it had made it clear to Baroness Denton that it was
'not in our interest to close down any viable business'. Barclays said: 'If
it is a viable business, we are never going to pull the plug.'
</TEXT>
