FT  19 AUG 92 / MPs favour longer stamp duty holiday
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SURVEY of MPs suggests most favour extending the suspension of stamp duty.
An Access Opinion survey of 100 MPs shows 65 per cent of Tories and 67 per
cent of Labour MPs want abolition of the tax.
Just 12 per cent of MPs want the tax re-imposed and 15 per cent would like
to see its re-introduction delayed until the housing market picks up.
Mr Clive Soley, MP for Hammersmith and a former Labour housing spokesman,
said yesterday that the government must reconsider its stance on housing
policy and financing.
'In the present circumstances it is probably a good idea to get rid of stamp
duty, but the underlying message is that housing finance is in an appalling
mess and they need to start from the beginning again,' he said.
But Mr Quentin Davies, Tory MP for Stamford and Spalding and a member of the
Commons Treasury select committee, said the experiment had been 'absolutely
useless'.
Mr Keith Vaz, Labour environment spokesman, called for the suspension to be
extended until there was an upturn in the housing market.
