<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 92 / Unlikely star finds a different TV role: Raymond Snoddy on
the Canadian broadcaster that may be a model for Channel Five
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A VICTORIAN building in downtown Toronto may become the model for Britain's
fifth terrestrial television channel.
CityTV, an influential voice in the shaping of Channel 5, has pioneered a
'high-energy' local broadcasting style, producing two 24-hour-a-day channels
from Wesley Buildings, the former headquarters of a publishing company.
Wesley Buildings is the star of the station  - the entire building is the
studio. There are 36 camera connection points around it. Grids for mounting
cameras cover the ceilings. Lights are rigged ready for an interview or a
piece to camera in the boardroom and office of Mr Moses Znaimer, the
station's founder and executive producer. He is also the consultant
executive producer to the consortium which is the only bidder for Channel 5.
Programmes are broadcast live from his office, from corridors, a balcony,
the car park or the station shop.
Mr Jay Switzer, the station manager, says: 'We do heavy-metal groups from
the sub-basement for the atmosphere and we even did Phil Collins from the
washroom.' He is a consultant to Channel 5 on the 'model'  - the term for
the mixture of music, films and local news that has put CityTV second in the
competitive Toronto television market.
The station, which has a staff of 390, is informal, mildly irreverent and
aimed at 18-49-year-olds. Analysts say it has a turnover of CDollars 60m
(Pounds 26m) to CDollars 90m and is increasingly profitable, in spite of the
recession. Costs are said to be about four times cheaper than conventional
television.
Bureaucracy is kept to a minimum. It is up to producers to find the right
people. 'We pick the people who can lead the life,' says Mr Switzer. 'We
want people who live the beat and can learn the television skills.'
Some top producers started as switchboard operators. Editors working on news
clips tell the audience what stories they are working on to promote the
news. 'We glamorise the process not the conclusions,' says Mr Switzer. 'Some
production assistants get more fan mail than the presenters.'
Mr Znaimer believes that, if the CityTV formula succeeds in London, 'the
world will come flocking to the model; if not it could remain a Toronto
curiosity'.
The Independent Television Commission is assessing the bid from the
consortium, which is led by Thames Television. The consortium has to
persuade the ITC that it can retune millions of video recorders likely to
suffer interference from the Channel 5 signal.
'It's looking more encouraging,' says Mr Znaimer. The bid is backed by Thorn
EMI, the parent of Thames. Sony Pictures, the Hollywood studio group, has
renewed its interest and there have been initial discussions with Viacom,
the US media group.
Potential investors in Channel 5, which plans to launch first in London,
then in Manchester followed by other UK cities have already raised the
possibility of going to other countries. Eventually Mr Znaimer believes
large cities all over the world will have their equivalents of CityTV.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-7347</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CHTBJAABFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920819
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 92 / Full employment promoted as Labour objective
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RESTORATION of full employment as one of the core aims of the Labour
movement will take a further step forward next month at the annual Trades
Union Congress conference in Blackpool.
The slogan, Working For Full Employment, will be the rallying call of a TUC
initiative to re-establish full employment as a central goal of economic
policy.
The idea has 'slipped down the agenda', a TUC official said. 'We want to
reassert it  - it is a time when we are having to reassess our priorities.'
Mr Frank Dobson, shadow employment secretary, recently called for full
employment to be put back at the heart of Labour policy. He said it would
never be achieved again unless restored to 'its proper place in the
political and economic ambitions of our country and the rest of the European
Community'.
Mr Dobson has twice returned to this theme, and has sought to broaden
support for his stance by arguing that mass unemployment is 'bad for all of
us' and not just for the unemployed.
Doubts remain about Mr Dobson's precise definition of full employment and
the full policy implications, but he is gathering some powerful allies in
the party. Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, said recently
he would 'very much share' Mr Dobson's sentiments.
Mr Murray Elder, chief of staff for Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, said
Mr Dobson's call to put full employment 'back at the top of the European
agenda' was 'entirely consistent with our position'.
Full employment was a Labour commitment for many years, but the party's
general election manifesto this year confined itself to pledging 'a swift
reduction in unemployment' and 'to prevent long-term unemployment, rather
than just trying to cope with it after it has occurred'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 7
</PAGE>
