<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 92 / International Company News: Conrad Black wins more time in
Daily News talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR and BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE STRUGGLE to find a new owner for the Daily News, the New York city
tabloid, intensi fied yesterday afternoon when a bankruptcy court judge
essentially extended the negotiation period to allow unions to try to reach
agreements with Mr Conrad Black, the Canadian publisher whose offer has
received management backing.
In the absence of a consensus among the paper's nine unions, Daily News
management voted to accept a bid by Mr Black, who controls The Daily
Telegraph of London, as part of its reorganisation plan presented to the
bankruptcy court yesterday.
Yesterday Judge Tina Brozman gave the parties until September 8 to reach a
firm agreement. Although Mr Black's proposal has met with management and
creditor approval, it also calls for agreements with all of the News unions,
which may prove impossible.
Other terms of Mr Black's offer include Dollars 75m for all of the Daily
News business assets, including Dollars 22m for administrative claims and
creditors, and the construction of a Dollars 200m colour printing plant in
New York city. Mr Black would also advance up to Dollars 3m in financing to
forestall a cash crisis, provided he reaches agreements with at least six of
the unions.
Before yesterday's hearing, the bulk of the unions were believed to favour a
competing bid from Mr Mortimer Zuckerman, owner of US News and World Report
magazine.
Mr Fred Drasner, president of US News and World Report, said the court
hearing was 'largely a non-event. Whoever wins an agreement with the unions
will be the owner of the Daily News. We will continue our discussions and
remain cautiously optimistic'. The Daily News, which celebrated being
rescued by Mr Robert Maxwell early last year, has been operating under the
protection of Chapter 11 of the US bankruptcy code since shortly after Mr
Maxwell's death.
Ms Brozman, who has grown increasingly frustrated with the continued impasse
at the Daily News, earlier chastised unions and management for 'jeopardising
my ability to keep this newspaper alive'.
Hollinger, the fast-growing newspaper group controlled by Mr Conrad Black,
lifted net second-quarter earnings almost sevenfold, thanks to the proceeds
of the recent sale of shares by the UK's Telegraph group, writes Bernard
Simon in Toronto.
Earnings for the quarter, including extraordinary items, were CDollars 85.8m
(USDollars 72.1m), or CDollars 1.50 a share, up from CDollars 12.3m, or 15
cents a share, a year earlier. Net earnings for the first six months climbed
to CDollars 54.1m, or 87 cents a share, from CDollars 29.7m, or 39 cents a
share, a year earlier. Revenues rose to CDollars 436.6m from CDollars
398.9m.
The company said that higher taxes stemming from the rise in operating
earnings and last year's application of loss carry-forwards resulted in a
fall in first-half operating earnings to CDollars 24.1m from CDollars 27.5m.
Operating earnings before income taxes and minority interest rose to
CDollars 57m from CDollars 46m.
The company said that 'other items' in the first half consisted almost
entirely of the CDollars 38.4m write-down taken in the first quarter
relating to the sale of its investment in United Newspapers, and the
second-quarter gain from the Telegraph sale.
</TEXT>
