<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 92 / UK Company News: Administrators appointed at Burns-Anderson
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BURNS-ANDERSON, the recruitment and financial services group formerly
chaired by Sir John Harvey-Jones, has gone into administrative receivership.
Touche Ross announced yesterday that insolvency partners Mr Nick Lyle and Mr
David Morgan had been appointed joint administrative receivers of the
holding company late on Friday evening.
Mr Lyle was also appointed joint administrative receiver, with Mr Ken Chalk
of Touche Ross, of Burns-Anderson Recruitment.
Dealings in the shares were suspended at 2p on Friday, after talks aimed at
restructuring the company's debts with its bankers, which include National
Westminster, failed.
The receivers also revealed yesterday that 16 of the 21 recruitment agency
offices of Burns-Anderson Recruitment were purchased over the weekend by
Premier Employment, a company newly formed by Mr Dorian Marks, the former
finance director.
Mr Marks, who was also a director of Burns-Anderson Recruitment, was
assisted in the purchase by other former directors.
Defending the swiftness of the disposal, Mr Chalk said that it had been 'a
good realisation for the creditors in the circumstances.'
Mr Chris Edge of Family Assurance Society, which has a 4.9 per cent stake in
the group, said yesterday that the developments over the weekend were 'not
an enormous surprise. The company has been struggling for a considerable
period.'
Pre-tax losses were Pounds 2.74m for the year to December 31 1991.
The group first fell into the red in the 15 months to end-December 1990.
Operating profits were Pounds 2.6m (Pounds 3.22m a year earlier) but
interest charges of Pounds 2.34m (Pounds 246,000) and exceptional costs of
Pounds 1.86m (nil) resulted in a pre-tax deficit of Pounds 1.6m (profit of
Pounds 2.98m).
Extraordinary costs of Pounds 5.25m relating to disposals and reorganisation
caused an overall deficit of Pounds 6.59m.
Burns-Anderson, which had interests in banking, hire-purchase, stockbroking,
insurance broking and direct marketing, sold most of these operations in
1990 to concentrate on its core businesses of independent financial advice
and recruitment.
The disposals reduced the group's borrowings from Pounds 35m to Pounds 15m.
The receivers said that three of the group's subsidiaries, including
Burns-Anderson Independent Network, the third largest network of financial
advisers in the country, were not immediately affected by the collapse of
the holding company.
Mr Alan Taylor, managing director of the network, which has 375 individually
registered members with Fimbra, the self-regulatory organisation, said
yesterday that the network itself continued to do business profitably and
was financially 'ringfenced' from the group.
Mr Stephen Kelland, director of Kelland &amp; Partners financial advisory
division, said yesterday that his company had no cross-guarantees with the
group.
'Whatever situation we move to will be a better one because the parent
company won't have debts,' he said.
The group's market capitalisation at the suspension price was Pounds
830,000, compared with a high of Pounds 55.5m in June 1987.
In that month, Sir John, former chairman of ICI and a renowned
troubleshooter, joined Burns-Anderson as non-executive chairman.
He resigned as chairman in June 1990, leaving the board in March 1991.
</TEXT>
