<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 92 / Four jailed after bullion trial: Large part of proceeds from
Pounds 26m Brink's-Mat robbery still missing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LARGE part of the spoils from Britain's biggest bullion robbery continues
to evade detectives some nine years and 12 trials after an armed gang
escaped with Pounds 26m in gold bars from a top security warehouse near
Heathrow Airport.
As four members of the criminal network that handled and conspired to handle
proceeds from the Brink's-Mat raid were sentenced yesterday to prison
sentences ranging from five to 10 years, police were still pondering what
had happened to part of the proceeds.
Mr Brian Perry and Mrs Jean Savage, who were convicted yesterday at the Old
Bailey of taking part in a plot to launder profits from the raid, received
sentences of nine years and five years respectively.
Fellow defendants who were convicted last week, Mr Gordon Parry and Mr
Patrick Clark, were sentenced to 10 years and six years. Mr Clark's son,
Stephen, was acquitted.
In the Brink's-Mat case - Britain's most notorious robbery since the Great
Train Robbery more than 20 years earlier - armed raiders threatened to turn
security guards into human torches to make them disclose the combination of
the vault.
Unlike the train robbers, however, the Brink's-Mat gang had evolved an
elaborate plan to convert the bullion into cash and launder the proceeds in
the international financial system.
Gold was melted down and sold on the open market by Mr Kenneth Noye, a Kent
businessman said to be the central linkman in the scheme. Noye was sentenced
in 1986 to 14 years in jail for his part in the plot. Previously he had been
acquitted of murder after stabbing a police officer who had been keeping his
home under surveillance.
Some Pounds 14m is thought to have been laundered through two groups using
the Noye route. Another route is so far undiscovered.
According to the prosecution, once the money had entered the banking system
it went on a merry-go-round between various banks and offshore institutions.
Initially, however, the money entered banks through large cash deposits. Mrs
Savage took a total of Pounds 2.5m of cash in shopping bags to a branch of
the Bank of Ireland in Croydon. The prosecution noted it was a lot of money
to be banked by a 'lady tobacconist'.
Her nest egg, which was later transferred to Dublin, grew to Pounds 4m with
interest before part of it was transferred to another bank account in Dubai.
That money was frozen by the courts before it could go further but other
profits from the raid were said by the prosecution to have been ploughed
back into property ventures, including some in London's Docklands.
Whether cash could be transferred into the bank system so easily today is
unlikely given the publication of Bank of England guidelines in 1990 which
urged banks and building societies to report suspicious transactions to the
police.
</TEXT>
