<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 92 / Timeshare buyers win right to cancel in cool-off period
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TIMESHARE BUYERS will soon have the right to cancel their transactions and
claim back advance payments, Baroness Denton, consumer affairs minister,
said yesterday.
The right to withdraw from a timeshare transaction within 14 days will apply
from October 12 and follows many complaints of misleading advertising and
high-pressure selling. The rule change also provides for cancelling credit
agreements. The right, contained in the Timeshare Act, will not apply where
the agreement is concluded outside the UK. The European Commission has said,
however, that it intends to issue a directive covering timeshare throughout
the EC.
The act has been criticised by the Timeshare Council for not going far
enough. The council, which represents timeshare owners and sellers, says it
wants to see better protection for purchasers' money through the use of
escrow accounts; the compulsory provision of full prospectuses to buyers;
and provisions to ensure that buyers acquire their timeshare free of
encumbrances such as pre-existing mortgages. The council also says that only
25 per cent of British purchasers buy timeshare in the UK so the majority
will not be protected by the changes.
Last month the Office of Fair Trading revoked the consumer credit licences
of six companies associated with Club Riviera, one of the UK's leading
timeshare groups. Sir Bryan Carsberg, OFT director-general, said a stream of
complaints against the companies had suggested that their conduct had been
'seriously misleading and deceptive'.
From October 12 a timeshare seller must provide a buyer with a notice
setting out the right to cancel and a blank cancellation form before the
agreement is signed. If the buyer is not given the notice or form, the right
to cancel extends indefinitely or until the buyer takes action that can be
construed as acceptance.
Failure by the seller to comply with the act could result in fines of up to
Pounds 5,000 on summary conviction or an un-limited amount on indictment.
Baroness Denton said she intended to use the UK's EC presidency to make
progress on the European directive.
</TEXT>
