<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 92 / West steps up pressure on Iraq: Southern air exclusion zone
planned in effort to counter violations of ceasefire terms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS, Middle East Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US, Britain and France plan to announce an air exclusion zone over
southern Iraq later this week in an attempt to protect Shia rebels from
attack and to increase pressure on the regime of President Saddam Hussein.
US officials say the three governments have agreed that 'blatant violations'
of UN ceasefire resolutions passed after the Gulf war can no longer be
tolerated.
It is expected that Iraq will be told, perhaps as early as tomorrow, that
helicopters and fixed-wing aircraft flying south of the 32nd parallel will
be shot down.
The White House declined to confirm the reports but said it was concerned
about the treatment of minorities in Iraq.
The announcement of an exclusion zone will be seen by some Arab governments
as another step towards the political partition of Iraq.
The Kurdish population in the north already benefits from air protection
above the 36th parallel. Some US officials believe that the increased
pressures on Saddam Hussein could lead to the collapse of his regime before
the end of the year.
The threat of an immediate military confrontation over UN access to
information on Iraqi weapons systems eased yesterday when inspectors in
Baghdad completed their present round of visits without incident. US
officials let it be known at the weekend that military action was being
prepared in case Iraq carried out its threat to bar the 22-strong inspection
team from government ministries.
It had been expected in Washington that the UN team would specifically ask
to enter the Ministry of Military Industrialisation. But in New York, Mr Tim
Trevan, spokesman for the UN inspections commission, said no request had
been lodged to visit ministries because there was no need to at this time.
'Of course, we retain the right to designate any location in Iraq,' he
added.
Mr Nikita Smidovich, the Russian who heads the team, said in Baghdad: 'We
have learned things that will be very useful and very helpful in our future
inspection activities.' He added that 'normal relations' had been restored
with Iraqi officials prior to yesterday's final round of inspections.
Oil prices initially rose on the threat of new hostilities, then slipped
back when Mr Smidovich said his team's mission had been successful. But the
market remained on edge about the possibility of western action over
southern Iraq.
President George Bush has vehemently denied that the threat of renewed
military action against Iraq was designed to boost his own flagging
re-election campaign. But in Indianapolis yesterday, on his way to the
Republican convention in Houston, he evoked the spirit of the Gulf war,
recalling that the US had 'kicked a little Baghdad bully'.
He added: 'Saddam Hussein miscalculated. He thought we'd grown soft over the
years. He didn't think we'd commit our armed forces. He mis-read the will of
the American people'.
If President Saddam did not give UN inspectors access to Iraqi government
buildings 'we have responses planned and they are strong responses'.
The US has in place all the military equipment it needs either to bomb
targets inside Iraq or enforce an air exclusion zone to the south of the
32nd parallel.
Aircraft movements in Iraq would be monitored principally by Awacs aircraft
flying out of bases in eastern Saudi Arabia, and supported by land and
carrier-based strike aircraft.
A specialised team of air warfare controllers was dispatched to Saudi Arabia
last week from its base in South Carolina.
The Saudi government, which has been concerned at the increasing signs of
Iraqi assertiveness, is believed to have agreed to the use of its bases for
US operations.
Iraq's challenge last month to UN inspection teams was only the latest
violation of UN resolutions, according to US officials. Resolution 688,
designed to deter Saddam Hussein from harassing domestic opposition groups,
has been ignored almost from the day it was approved.
The intensification of Iraqi army efforts to crush remaining Shia rebel
groups in the south have, however, reached a level which the White House
felt could no longer be ignored, in particular the use of fixed-wing
aircraft.
For many months after the conclusion of the Gulf war Iraq made no effort to
use fighter aircraft.
However, evidence of fixed-wing flights has been building up over the past
two months, leading Iraqi opposition groups to make direct appeals to the US
for protection.
Bush spurred by hopes that Saddam nearly finished, Page 4
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-7418</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CHTAOADBFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920818
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 92 / Companies fooled by 'cowboy' copier salesmen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SMOOTH-TALKING photocopier salesmen are swooping on smaller companies when
senior staff are on holiday and persuading their deputies to sign
extortionate contracts which can ruin the business.
The Confederation of British Industry warned yesterday that, with the boss
lying on a beach, some businesses back home are falling victim to 'cowboy'
salesmen pushing contracts with penal costs and conditions.
As a result, a number of unsuspecting companies are being forced to close
down, unable either to honour or cancel high cost agreements to which they
are committed for many years.
High-pressure sales techniques in some parts of the photocopier market are
well known but complaints from customers, who have found themselves on the
wrong end of a salesman's slick patter, have been rising.
The Campaign to Clean up Copier Contracts, which represents corporate
victims of the photocopier salesmen and is supported by the CBI, backed
yesterday's warning.
A campaign official said:'Some small businesses have found it easier to fold
than to pay the penalties arising from the copier contract.'
Companies are not regarded as consumers under the Consumer Credit Act and
are, therefore, unable to break contracts they have signed. The campaign
also wants churches, schools, charities and other corporate bodies to be
given the same protection under the law as individuals and partnerships.
It is calling for a mandatory, two-week cooling off period for photocopier
contracts and members plan to meet Baroness Denton, consumer affairs
minister, to press for action.
The campaign plans to publish a blacklist of companies which ignore the code
of practice drawn up by the British Association of Print and Copyshops.
Many companies are being caught out by the offer of a 'free' photocopying
machine, along with a service agreement which provides for payment at an
agreed rate for copies. Only in the small print, however, is it clear that
the cost per copy can be very high and can rise by up to 15 per cent during
each year of the contract.
Ms Judith Vincent, the CBI's head of company law, said yesterday: 'Vigilance
is vital if a company wants to avoid such extortion'. She said hundreds of
companies have been taken in by the malpractices of part of the photocopying
industry. She emphasised that contracts could contain costly extras and last
up to nine years, compared with the average three-year lifespan of a
photocopying machine.
</TEXT>
