FT  18 AUG 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If last week's programme was a good example, Shaking The Heavens is a
heartening series about the strengths of old age. Last week a poet, this
week a composer: Minna Keal used her pension as a student grant and now, at
83, has become a composer of serious music (7.45 BBC2).
There follows the first in a series, Floyd On Spain, (8.30) in which Keith
Floyd extends his culinary globe-trotting once again. If he can withstand
the blandishments of those who would turn him into another arm-waving,
cliche-spouting 'character' and stick to his natural good humour we shall be
in for another treat.
The star of BBC1's two-part drama Children Of The Dragon (9.30) is, yet
again, Bob Peck. The story, we are told, is of 'love and intrigue set in
1989 against the backdrop of the violent political events of Tiananmen
Square'.
BBC2 begins The John Bull Business (9.40), a series of five documentaries on
British business culture, with a programme which features Freddie Laker, the
man who took on the big airlines in the 1970s. . . and lost. He and others
discuss why in recent years it has been easier to get established in
business but also easier to fail.
