FT  18 AUG 92 / Lotus car losses triple to Pounds 15.8m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GROUP Lotus, the UK sports car maker and automotive engineering consultancy,
suffered a pre-tax loss of Pounds 14.7m last year, as the losses of its car
operations more than tripled to Pounds 15.8m.
The scale of the losses, revealed yesterday in the company's annual report,
has forced General Motors of the US to increase its financial commitment to
its troubled subsidiary.
GM took over Group Lotus for Pounds 22.7m in 1986. It has been forced to
pump in Pounds 18m to repair the Lotus balance sheet during 1991 including
the provision of Pounds 11.5m in new equity with the remainder coming in
subordinated debt.
The company has been hit by recession in its two main markets, the UK and
the US, but the biggest blow has been the commercial failure of its Lotus
Elan sports car.
Two months ago Lotus announced it was ceasing production of the Elan, its
main product, less than two-and-a-half years after the car was launched.
Group Lotus losses have grown from Pounds 2.1m in 1988 to Pounds 4.4m in
1989, Pounds 12.7m in 1990 and Pounds 14.7m last year on a turnover of only
Pounds 87.5m. According to the annual report the losses of the car
operations jumped from Pounds 4.6m in 1990 to Pounds 15.8m last year on a
turnover of Pounds 43.2m.
The cutbacks of the car operations masked the success of the Group Lotus
engineering consultancy and vehicle testing operations which increased
profits to Pounds 5.95m, from Pounds 1.56m a year earlier, on a turnover of
Pounds 44.3m, largely thanks to increased work from North America.
The scale of the overall group pre-tax loss was reduced by exceptional
profits of Pounds 5.5m (of which Pounds 3.53m was credited to the profit and
loss account) arising from the sale of its Millbrook Land subsidiary for
Pounds 7.8m in cash.
It also took a pension contribution holiday throughout 1991.
The exceptional profits were offset by redundancy costs totalling Pounds
2.3m.
The withdrawal of the Elan will lead to around 350 redundancies from the
company's 507-strong Lotus Cars workforce in Hethel, Norfolk.
In the first six months of this year Lotus car output has dropped by two
thirds to only 505 from 1,559 in the same period last year. Production
totalled 2,240 in the whole of 1991.
</TEXT>
